📖 Day 07 Journal
Date: Day 07
🎯 Goal
Build the first version of a calculator using JavaScript without copying code.
✅ What I Built
Calculator with two inputs.
Addition.
Subtraction.
Multiplication.
Division.
Result display.
Input validation.
User-friendly error messages.
🧠 Biggest Concepts I Learned
1. Execution timing matters.
The biggest bug was getting:
Your answer is 00
I learned that JavaScript executes code in order.
I placed Number() outside the click event, so it converted empty strings into 0 before the user typed anything.
Moving it inside the function fixed the issue.
2. Input values are strings.
HTML inputs always give strings.
"5" + "5"
becomes
"55"
Using
Number()
converts them into numbers so addition works correctly.
3. fn vs fn()
I finally understood the difference.
fn points to a function.
fn() executes the function.
This helped me understand event listeners.
4. Event listeners
Instead of
plus()
I now understand why we write
plus
The browser stores the function and waits until the click happens before executing it.
5. Validation is a decision tree.
I learned why
||
matched too early.
Changing the first condition to
&&
allowed JavaScript to continue checking the remaining conditions.
I also learned that the order of conditions changes program behavior.
6. Testing edge cases
I tested situations instead of assuming.
I discovered:
10 / 0 → Infinity
0 / 0 → NaN
0 / 10 → 0
Testing first helped me understand JavaScript's behavior.
🐛 Biggest Bugs
Calculator showing 00.
Using plus() instead of plus.
Confusing || and &&.
String concatenation instead of addition.
💡 Biggest Realization
Programming is not about writing code.
Programming is about asking:
"What is JavaScript thinking right now?"
That question helped me solve almost every bug today.
🏆 Personal Achievement
Today I finished my first JavaScript project.
More importantly, I wrote every line myself.
I hid my previous code while writing the other operations so I couldn't copy myself. That forced me to think and rebuild the logic from memory.
This project marks the point where I stopped relying on tutorials and started reasoning through problems.
